column1: Before 1 January 2020, will General Motors launch a ride-hailing service open to the public in the U.S. which uses autonomous vehicles?
column5: ['Yes, using only vehicles with steering wheels', 'Yes, using only vehicles without steering wheels', 'Yes, using at least some vehicles without steering wheels', 'No']
column6: ['Technology']
column11: General Motors and its subsidiary Cruise Automation have announced intentions to launch a ride-hailing service somewhere in the U.S. in 2019 (GM Authority). GM plans to use a version of the Chevy Bolt built without a steering wheel for the service (Detroit News, Driven, IEEE Spectrum). However, technical and regulatory hurdles remain (Reuters, San Francisco Chronicle). A service which requires rider prescreening or registration before use will count. A service that operates along a fixed route will not count. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: There are still a number of testing and verification required for this sort of service to be deemed safe.

As of 2019, Cruise is focusing on testing their vehicles in select cities. The company is testing its vehicles in various cities across California, Arizona, and Michigan. According to Ammann, “In order to reach the level of performance and safety validation required to deploy a fully driverless service in San Francisco, we will be significantly increasing our testing and validation miles over the balance of this year, which has the effect of carrying the timing of fully driverless deployment beyond the end of the year.”

Reports that GM plans to double head count for Cruise in the coming months: https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/03/13/gm-doubles-down-self-driving-with-a-planned-hiring.aspx I am not saying that doubling head count will double the probability as might be inferred when comparing my previous forecast with this one, but I now think my previous forecast was a bit too pessimistic to start with. It surely will take 2-3 months to hire that many staff and get them to full productivity. That leaves ~6 months to roll out the service, which is not impossible but ambitious. It's also hard to judge how far along they are right now and whether the hiring spree is an indication that they know how to push it over the finish line, or whether it is an act to compensate for lagging behind schedule.
Given the regulatory hurdles they still face, and the lack of apparent progress resolving them, I am shifting a bit toward no.

As the technology industry continues research and development in field of autonomous machines, the hope for autonomous vehicles is growing and becoming closer to application. GM CEO Mary Barra is directing the company into a path to which she believes the future will focus on, which is self-driving cars in the drive-hailing service. However, as this gets closer to becoming a reality, the issues it brings are becoming more obvious. There are policies and laws that have yet to be addressed when it comes to autonomous vehicles on the road. These cars may have difficulty accounting for certain laws of the road and for humans' improv on the road. Should a crash occur, the question of fault who come into play as one wouldn't know who to attribute the mistake too. With this, then you would have to look at whether it was the hardware or software of the autonomous car. GM must also listen to its audience; many of whom show large amounts of apprehension in placing themselves or loved ones in a car without a driver. Because of these reasons, the likelihood of GM launching an autonomous vehicle hauling service is unlikely in the time span of less than a year.

GM's petition to NHTSA is going forward with a public comment period, which will probably last 60 days [1]. On the other hand, the public seems wary of AVs [2] and may not welcome a vehicle without a steering wheel or break pedal.

Despite saying they will launch this in 2019, the only thing in evidence is that they've recruited a lot of money (from Honda, SoftBank) to throw at it. Many people cite Waymo's long road to launch as evidence this is impossible, but we know the pioneer has a disproportionate share of the burden for new tech. Plus, American car companies are desperate for a win, and I could see GM throwing a lot of resources into a Pyrrhic victory of second-to-market. This is one I'll have to update a lot over the next year as new developments occur. The no-steering-wheels thing is a fun red herring, but seems only slightly more likely than a car without brakes. I doubt we're close to allowing cars in which humans could not physically steer the car if they had to. It's just too counter-intuitive for legislators that still think people at Google are hand-selecting your search results to make them more anti-Republican.
